Description of simulations

We inform our model to losely match the fishery dynamics observed for the VDS operated by the PNA. The table below contains the values used to parameterize the model.

Define parameters

# Reserve properties
theta <- 1
R <- 0

# Bio
MSY <- 1875600 # 50th percentile from MSY in table 8 of SA (https://www.wcpfc.int/node/27490)
Bmsy <- 1628000 # 50th percentile from SBmsy in table 8 of SA (https://www.wcpfc.int/node/27490)
K <- 6876526 # 50th percentile from SB_f0 in table 8 of SA (https://www.wcpfc.int/node/27490)
Bc_B0 <- 0.51 # 50th percentile from SBlatest/SB_fo in table 8 of SA (https://www.wcpfc.int/node/27490)
Cnow <- 1679444 # Catches now
Bnow <- K * Bc_B0 # current Biomass (2012 - 2015 average)
r <- 0.57 # From fishbase: Prior r = 0.57, 95% CL = 0.41 - 0.78 (https://www.fishbase.in/summary/107#)

# Economic
beta <- 1.3
p <- 1100 # (1447 + 1467) / 2 #mean between thailand and japan values (Value of WCPFC-CA tuna fisheries 2017 report)
E <- 45000
q <- 12 / (0.1 * Bnow) # 2 * (0.8 * Cnow) / (E * 0.8 * Bnow)
c <- 180 # 340

# Vectors of initial biomass and movement
# Proportional size of the high seas
prop_hs <- 0.1
# Number of patches
n_patches <- 10
# Biomass redistribution vector
fvec <- c(rep(((1 - prop_hs) / (n_patches - 1)), (n_patches - 1)), prop_hs)
# fvec <- c(0.12, 0.08, 0.07, 0.13, 0.07, 0.12, 0.09, 0.12, 0.1, 0.1)
names(fvec) <- c("KIR", "FSM", "MHL", "NRU", "PLW", "PNG", "SLB", "TKL", "TUV", "HS")
Xvec <- Bnow * fvec

We use the model above run three different simulations. We test the model across a range reserve sizes and movement parameters. We use to main scenarios. The first scenario does not allow trading. In this case, total allowable effort (\(\bar{E}\)) and biomass \(B_{now}\) are known and equally distributed among patches 1-9. For patch 10, we solve for Ei until biomass converges to match \(B_{now}\). We then proceed to ``closeââ a portion of Patch 1, and calculate the vessel-day price in Patch 1 given that only \(X_i\Omega_i\) biomass is available for harvest. We compare vessel-day revenues of each scenario to a case with no reserve (\(R = 0\)). This produces a measure of the cost of implementing a spatial closure of size \(R\) in patch 1.

The second scenario allows trading. We start again by solving for the high seas to obtain total effort. Since a closure is not in effect, this equiulibrium is the same as the first step above. We then implement a spatial closure in patch 1. This essentially lowers the price fishers would be willing to pay to fish in a patch with biomass \(X_i\Omega_i\), lowering demand for vessel-days in pach 1. Patches 2 - 9 have a higher demand for vessel days, and therefore a portion of vessel-days from patch 1 are sold to patches 2 - 9. This increases effort in these patches, which reduces escapement and therefore biomass. This reduction in biomass in turn would modify the demand curves (Ei). We therefore iterate this process until biomass stabilizes, therefore finding the systemâs equilibrium. Like before, we calculate vessel-day revenues to each patch and compare them to a case with no reserve in patch 1.

Cost of a reserve is governed by fish movement

Less movement leads to higer costs

This first par uses no trading, but allows us to look at how movement (\(\theta\)) governs costs. The intuition is that, given the parameterization, high movement rates will lead to low costs because:

\[\Omega = \theta + (1 - \theta)(1 - R)\]

This shows that, no matter what the size of the reserve is, when \(\theta = 1\), \(\Omega = 1\).

Get initial conditions

We first run a model that allows for trading to get the Effort vector that would maximize \(pi\).

Benchmark_results <-
  PNA_with_trading(
    fvec = fvec,
    theta = theta,
    R = R,
    r = r,
    K = K,
    p = p,
    q = q,
    Xvec = Xvec,
    beta = beta,
    c = c,
    E = E

Run the model

We now run the model with NO trading, using the Evec above as starting condition.

# Create an empty tibble to store the results in the process
Rvec <- seq(0, 1, 0.05)
thetavec <- seq(0, 1, 0.1)

DF_results_no_trading <-
  expand.grid(R = Rvec, theta = thetavec) %>%
  mutate(
    res = map2(
      theta,
      R,
      PNA_no_trading,
      fvec = fvec,
      r = r,
      K = K,
      p = p,
      q = q,
      Xvec = Xvec,
      beta = beta,
      c = c,
      Evec = Evec
    )
  ) %>%
  unnest()

We now take these results and add the benchmark results (no reserve) to calculate the cost of the reserve as the change in revenue. The proportional way of saying this is:

\[ \%C_R = \frac{\Pi_{R = 0} - \Pi_{R = r}}{\Pi_{R = 0}} \] Where \(\Pi_{R = 0}\) is the vessel-day revenue when there is no reserve, hence the \(R = 0\) subindex. The \(\Pi_{R = r}\) denotes the vessel-day revenues when reserve has size (\(r \in (0, 1)\)). The vessel-day revenue is simply the vessel-day price times the number of vessel-days in patch \(i\): \(\pi \times E_i\).

DF_1_no_trading <- DF_results_no_trading %>%
  filter(Country == "KIR") %>%
  left_join(Benchmark_results, by = "Country") %>%
  mutate(
    cost = b_vdsrevenue - VDSrevenue,
    rel_cost = cost / b_vdsrevenue,
    cost_pna_not_kir = VDSrevenue_notKIR - b_vdsrevenue_notKIR,
    rel_cost_pna_not_kir = cost_pna_not_kir / b_vdsrevenue_notKIR
  )

We can now go ahead and plot these results. The figure below shows the \(C_R\) defined above for different size of reserves \(R\) in the x-axis, given values of \(theta\) (colors). The graph shows how a smaller movement rate leads to increased costs to the country that implements the reserve. A movement of \(\theta = 1\) implies no reserve, and thus leads to no losses. However, this parameter is unlikely. We also see how the losses are not proportional to 1. That is, a 10% closure does not lead to a 10% loss in profits.

Is this due to the concavity in costs? i.e.Â the \(\beta\) parameter$?

Yes, it looks like a \(\beta = 1.1\) actually reduces this.

Allocation rules matter

Allocation rules

In the second scenario above, effort from a patch with conservation is traded to other patches. This means that its allocation will decrease as purse seine effort in its EEZ is reduced. After solving for the new equilibrium for each combination of \(R\) and \(\theta\), we project the fishery 50 years in time. At the end of every time, vessel-days are allocated to each patch based on the following rule:

\[ E_i^* = \alpha \left(\frac{\sum_{\tau = 0}^{\hat{\tau}}E_{i,t-\tau}}{\bar{E}\hat{\tau}} \right) + (1 - \alpha) \left(\frac{\sum_{\tau = 0}^{\hat{\tau}}X_{i,t-\tau}}{\bar{X}\hat{\tau}} \right) \]

Where \(\alpha\) is a weight on historical effort (\(E_i\)) and \(1-\alpha\) is the weight in historical biomass (\(B_i\)). We use \(\hat{\tau}= 7\) to obtain a moving mean of 7 years for these measures. The difference between allocated days (\(E_i^*\)) and used days (determined by Eq: ) for patch 1 are the sales. We then calculate vessel-day revenues to each country over the 50-year time horizon and compare them to a case where there is no reserve and allocations are based solely on biomass (\(\alpha = 0\)).

source(here("scripts", "model", "allocate.R"))
source(here("scripts", "model", "allocate_wrap.R"))
source(here("scripts", "model", "move_in_time.R"))
source(here("scripts", "model", "move_in_time_no_trading.R"))

We first obtain the optimal allocation by running the model until steady state and with no reserves.

alphas <- c(0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1)

delta <- 1 / 1.1

plan(multiprocess)

allocation <-
  expand.grid(
    R = Rvec,
    theta = c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75),
    alpha = alphas,
    trade = T
  ) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  mutate(
    resutls = future_pmap(
      .l = list(
        alpha = alpha,
        R = R,
        theta = theta,
        trade = trade
      ),
      .f = allocate_wrap, 
      fvec = fvec,
      r = r,
      K = K,
      p = p,
      q = q,
      Xvec = Xvec,
      beta = beta,
      c = c,
      E = E
    )
  ) %>%
  unnest() %>%
  filter(country == "KIR") %>%
  mutate(
    rev_dir = Ei * pi,
    deltaE = Ea - Ei,
    rev_sells = deltaE * pi,
    rev_tot = rev_dir + rev_sells,
    fct = delta ^ year,
    rev_tot_disc = rev_tot * fct
  )

best_rev <- allocate_wrap(
  alpha = 0,
  R = 0,
  theta = 0.5,
  trade = T,
  fvec = fvec,
  r = r,
  K = K,
  p = p,
  q = q,
  Xvec = Xvec,
  beta = beta,
  c = c,
  E = E
) %>%
  filter(country == "KIR") %>%
  mutate(
    rev_dir = Ei * pi,
    deltaE = Ea - Ei,
    rev_sells = deltaE * pi,
    rev_tot = rev_dir + rev_sells,
    fct = delta ^ year,
    rev_tot_disc = rev_tot * fct
  ) %$%
  sum(rev_tot)
(allocation_cost_plot <- allocation %>%
   filter(R > 0,
          trade) %>% 
   mutate(trade = ifelse(trade, "Trading", "No Trading"),
          theta = as.character(theta)) %>% 
   group_by(trade, alpha, R, theta) %>%
   summarize(rev = sum(rev_tot)) %>%
   ungroup() %>%
   mutate(cost = (best_rev - rev) / best_rev) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = R, y = cost, color = alpha, group = paste(alpha, theta), linetype = theta)) +
   geom_line(size = 1.5) +
   scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
   xlab("Portion of patch as reserve (R)") +
   ylab("Costs\n(% of case with R = 0)") +
   scale_color_viridis_c() +
   scale_linetype_manual(values = c("solid", "dashed", "dotted")) +
   ggtheme_plot() +
   # facet_wrap(~trade, ncol = 1) +
   guides(color = guide_colorbar(title = quo("Allocation\nparameter ("~alpha~")"),
                                 ticks.colour = "black",
                                 frame.colour = "black"),
          linetype = guide_legend(title = quo("Movement\nparameter ("~theta~")"),
                                  override.aes = list(size = 0.5))))
